</table>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Phenomenon" title="Phenomenon">phenomenon</a> of drug <a href="/wiki/Addiction" title="Addiction">addiction</a> has occurred to some degree throughout recorded <a href="/wiki/History" title="History">history</a> (see "<a href="/wiki/Opium" title="Opium">opium</a>"). Modern <a href="/wiki/Agriculture" title="Agriculture">agricultural</a> practices, improvements in access to drugs, advancements in <a href="/wiki/Biochemistry" title="Biochemistry">biochemistry</a>, and dramatic increases in the recommendation of drug usage by clinical practitioners have exacerbated the problem significantly in the 20th century. Improved means of active biological agent manufacture and the introduction of synthetic compounds, such as <a href="/wiki/Methamphetamine" title="Methamphetamine">methamphetamine</a> are also factors contributing to drug addiction.<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54" title=""><span>[</span>55<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
